questions.scenario:
The backend exposes routes like `/users` and `/orders`. Requests through Nginx to `/api/users` return 404. The config is:

```nginx
location /api/ {
    proxy_pass http://127.0.0.1:3000;
}
```

The upstream capture shows `GET /api/users`. Which `proxy_pass` line should be used if Nginx is meant to strip `/api/`?

A different backend is built with routes under `/api`, including `/api/users`. The Nginx config is:

```nginx
location /api/ {
    proxy_pass http://127.0.0.1:3000/;
}
```

Clients get 404 because the backend receives `/users`. Which fix matches the backend router?

A reverse proxy works functionally, but the app generates redirect URLs pointing at `http://localhost:3000` instead of `https://api.example.com`. The config lacks:

```nginx
proxy_set_header Host $host;
proxy_set_header X-Forwarded-Proto $scheme;
```

What is the best explanation?

A production proxy block is being reviewed:

```nginx
location / {
    proxy_pass http://localhost:3000;
    proxy_set_header Host $host;
    proxy_set_header X-Real-IP $remote_addr;
    proxy_set_header X-Forwarded-For $proxy_add_x_forwarded_for;
    proxy_set_header X-Forwarded-Proto $scheme;
}
```

Which statements accurately describe these headers?
